nts in public?</strong> Very unlikely, sadly, as despite giving him a fairly average mark for his academic work, his students awarded him a red chilli pepper for \"hotness\" on <a href=\"http://www.ratemyprofessors.com/\" title=\"\">ratemyprofessors.com</a>.</p><p><strong>It's what every professor yearns for, along with tenure.</strong> Yes. Although Brat might also put less government and more Jesus on his list. And he might be forgiven a bit of celebratory nudeness because his victory in the primary was truly astonishing.</p><p><strong>How so?</strong> He defeated Eric Cantor, the house majority leader and the second most senior Republican in the House of Representatives, who has held the seat for 14 years.</p><p><strong>Goodness.</strong> And with a  <a href=\"http://www.vox.com/2014/6/10/5798582/eric-cantor-is-toast\" title=\"\">$200,000 campaign, compared with </a>Cantor's $5.4m.</p><p><strong>Wow.</strong> No poll predicted that Brat would win, and no house majority leader has lost their primary <a href=\"http://www.msnbc.com/the-last-word/eric-cantor-loses-gop-primary-dave-brat\" title=\"\">since the post was created in 1899</a>.</p><p><strong>Crumbs and crikey.</strong> \"I was blessed,\" Brat says. \"It's a miracle.\"</p><p><strong>Not if you're Cantor.</strong> <strong>How did Brat convince the voters to support him?</strong> He threatened them with immigrants.</p><p><strong>Of course.</strong> There is a debate in Washington over whether some people who entered the US illegally should be allowed to stay. Cantor hinted that he might be willing to consider compromises. <a href=\"http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/johncassidy/2014/06/eric-cantor-loses-to-david-brat.html\" title=\"\">Brat pounced</a>.</p><p><strong>Will he win the district too?</strong> Hard to say. It's been solidly Republican since 1971, but not all Republican voters will like Brat's Tea Party ways.</p><p><strong>Who's he up against?</strong> That's another funny thing. The Democratic candidate is a guy called Jack Trammell, who is – wait for it – another professor at Randolph-Macon College with a chilli pepper against his name.</p><p><strong>That's democracy, I suppose. </strong>Yes. A form of it.</p><p><strong>Do say:</strong> \"Take up thy bed and walk …\"</p><p><strong>Don't say:</strong> \"… back to Mexico.\"</p>","headline":"Dave Brat: 'hot' Tea Party backed challenger causes US political shock","trailText":"A devout Catholic and social conservative, he defeated Eric Cantor, the majority leader in the House of Representatives, in the Virginia primary","newspaperPageNumber":"3","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/6/11/1402487676847/Dave-Brat-hot-stuff.-004.jpg","wordcount":"353","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"439123212","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"9151939","isPremoderated":"false","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-06-12T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2107994","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-06-18T12:10:28Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/world/shortcuts/2014/jun/11/dave-brat-tea-party-eric-cantor-us-political-shock","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/world/shortcuts/2014/jun/11/dave-brat-tea-party-eric-cantor-us-political-shock","tags":[{"id":"world/us-politics","webTitle":"US politics","type":"keyword","sectionId":"world","sectionName":"World news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/world/us-politics","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/world/us-politics","references":[]},{"id":"world/tea-party-movement","webTitle":"Tea Party movement","type":"keyword","sectionId":"world","sectionName":"World news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/world/tea-party-movement","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/world/tea-party-movement","references":[]},{"id":"world/eric-cantor","webTitle":"Eric Cantor","type":"keyword","sectio